Europe. This book proposes an exploration of European videogames, including both analyses of transnational aspects of European production and close readings of national specificities. It offers a kaleidoscope of European videogame culture, focusing on the analysis of European works and creators but also addressing contextual aspects and placing videogames within a wider sociocultural and philosophical ground. The aim of this collective work is to contribute to the creation of a, so far, almost non-existent yet necessary academic endeavour: a story of the works, authors, styles and cultures of the European videogame.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aVideo games industryzEurope. 0aVideo gameszEurope. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aGame Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 7aNON-CLASSIFIABLE.2bisacsh  aEurope, video game, culture, design, representation.1 aBlanchet, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández-Vara, Clara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarin, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGualeni, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarhulahti, Veli-Matti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMortensen, Torill Elvira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavarro-Remesal, Víctor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavarro-Remesal, Víctor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNewman, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliva, Mercè, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaasonen, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato